{{Socialism sidebar}}
'''Marhaenism''' ({{lang-ind|Marhaenisme}}) is a [[socialism|socialistic]] political ideology originating in [[Indonesia]]. An adherent of Marhaenism is known as a '''Marhaenist'''. It was developed by the first [[President of Indonesia]], [[Sukarno]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Leifer|first1=Michael|title=Dictionary of the modern politics of South-East Asia|date=2001|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0415238755|edition=3rd}}</ref>
Some scholars argue that Marhaenism is a variant of [[Marxism]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lev|first1=Daniel S.|title=The transition to guided democracy : Indonesian politics, 1957-1959|date=2009|publisher=Equinox Publishing|location=Jakarta|isbn=978-6028397407|edition=[New ed.].}}</ref> It emphasizes national unity, culture, and collectivist economics. It was established as an [[anti-capitalism|anti-capitalist]] and [[anti-imperialism|anti-imperialist]] ideology. It promotes democratic rights in opposition to [[authoritarianism]], while condemning [[liberalism]] and [[individualism]]. It combines both western and eastern principles.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Holt|first1=[edited by] Claire|title=Culture and politics in Indonesia|date=2007|publisher=Equinox Pub.|location=Jakarta|isbn=978-9793780573|edition=1st Equinox}}</ref> Marhaenism is the guiding ideology of the [[Indonesian National Party Marhaenism]] and the now defunct [[Parti Marhaen Malaysia]].
==History==
The name of the ideology is said to be taken that of a land-poor farmer named Marhaen, whom Sukarno met in [[Priangan]]. Sukarno attributed the farmer's poverty to a lack of access to production tools. Sukarno thenceforth took to referring to members of the agrarian class as "Marhaens".<ref>{{cite book|author=Soekarno|title=Pokok-pokok ajaran marhaenisme menurut Bung Karno|date=2004|publisher=Media Pressindo|location=Yogyakarta|isbn=978-9799222923|edition=Cet. 3.}}</ref>
