== Background ==
{{See also|Crusades|Norman conquest of southern Italy|Photian schism}}
'''867'''
* ''Late summer.'' [[Photios I of Constantinople|Photios I]], the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople]] condems practices of the [[Latin Church]]{{mdash}}especially the addition of the phrase ''"[[filioque]]"'' ("and from the [[God the Son|Son]]") to the [[Nicene Creed]] and the liturgical use of [[unleavened bread]]{{mdash}}and [[Excommunication|excommunicates]] [[Pope Nicholas I]].{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=454}}{{sfn|Harris|2003|p=48}} 
'''869'''
* ''Late.'' [[Pope Adrian II]] achieves the denunciation of Photios at a council of the Byzantine prelates.{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=456}}
'''969'''
* ''October.'' The Byzantines re-capture Antioch that they lost to the Arabs in 637.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=14}}
'''1016'''
* [[Melus of Bari|Melus]], a [[Lombards|Lombard]] nobleman from [[Bari]], approaches [[Duchy of Normandy|Norman]] pilgrims at the shrine of [[Michael (archangel)|Michael the Archangel]] on Mount [[Gargano]] (in southern Italy), seeking their assistance against the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]].{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=9}}
'''1017'''
* ''Summer.'' Norman warriors come to the Lombard [[Principality of Capua]].{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=19}}
'''1046'''
* [[Robert Guiscard]]{{mdash}}a younger son of a petty Normandian baron{{mdash}}settles in southern Italy.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|pp=39, 68}}
'''1050s'''
* The Normans introduce Latin practices in the Greek churches in southern Italy.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=99}}{{sfn|Harris|2003|p=50}}
'''1052'''
* Patriarch [[Michael I Cerularius]] closes all Latin churches in Constantinople.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=99}}{{sfn|Harris|2003|p=50}}
'''1054'''
* ''July 16.'' The late [[Pope Leo IX]]'s three envoys excommunicate Patriarch Cerularius. The event develop into a [[East–West Schism|lasting schism between the Roman Catholic and Orthodox churches]].{{sfn|Norwich|1992|pp=103-105}}
'''1059'''
* ''Late August.'' [[Treaty of Melfi]]: [[Pope Nicholas II]] confirms Robert Guiscard as [[prince of Capua]] and authorizes him to conquer the [[Emirate of Sicily]].{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=127}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=14}}  
'''1071'''
* ''August 21.'' [[Battle of Manzikert]]: the [[Seljuk Empire|Seljuk Sultan]] [[Alp Arslan]] routes and captures the [[Byzantine Emperor]] [[Romanos IV Diogenes]]. The Seljuks start invading [[Asia Minor]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=15}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=42}}
'''1070s'''
* A Byzantine general of Armenian origin, [[Philaretos Brachamios]], tooks control of large territories in northern Syria.{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=610}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=2 (note 3)}}
'''1078'''
* The Byzantine Emperor [[Nikephoros III Botaneiates]] appoints Brachamios as duke (or governor) of Antioch and ''[[domestikos]]'' (or commander-in-chief) of the East, thus legitimizing Brachamios' hold of northern Syria and [[Cibyrrhaeot Theme|Cilicia]].{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|pp=610, 613}}
'''1081'''
* ''Early.'' Robert Guiscard sends his eldest son, [[Bohemond I of Antioch|Bohemond]], to make preparations for his invasion of the Byzantine Empire.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=227}}
'''1082'''
* ''February 21.'' Robert Guiscard takes Dyrrachium (now [[Durrës]] in Albania) in the Byzantine Empire.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|pp=228, 233}}
'''1083'''
* ''Summer.'' The Byzantines and the Venetians chase the Normans from Dyrrachium.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|pp=243-244}}{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=615}}
'''{{circa}} 1084'''
* The Seljuks capture Antioch.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=2 (note 3)}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=18}}{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=616}}
'''1085'''
* ''July 17.'' Robert Guiscard dies. Bohemond is disinherited in favor of his half-brother, [[Roger Borsa]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=18}}{{sfn|Norwich|1992|pp=195-196}}
* ''Autumn.'' Bohemond seizes the [[Principality of Taranto]] in southern Italy.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|pp=259-260}}
'''1095'''
* ''March.'' The deputies of the Byzantine Emperor [[Alexios I Komnenos]] ask [[Pope Urban II]] at the [[Council of Piacenza]] to facilitate the recruitment of troops in Western Europe to fight against the Seljuks.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=20}}{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=619}}
* ''November 27.'' At the [[Council of Clermont]], Urban II proclaims the [[First Crusade]] for the liberation of the [[Holy Land]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=20}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=4}}
* ''December 1.'' [[Raymond IV, Count of Toulouse]] is the first ruler to take the Cross in token of his decision to join the crusade.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=20}}{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=50}}
'''1096'''
* ''September.'' Bohemond assists Roger Borsa in besieging [[Amalfi]], but he abandons the siege as soon as he is informed of the crusade.{{sfn|Jotischky|2017|p=50}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|pp=20-21}}
* ''October 26.'' Bohemond departs from [[Bari]], accompanied by hundreds of Norman warriors, including his nephew, [[Tancred, Prince of Galilee|Tancred]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=21}}{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=277}}
'''1097'''
* ''January–February.'' Clashes between Bohemond's troops and Byzantine communities during Bohemond's march towards Constantinople on the Via Egnatia.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=106}} 
* ''April 22.'' Bohemond cannot convince Alexios I to appoint him as the supreme commander of the crusader army, but he swears allegiance to the Emperor, also promising to return all former Byzantine territories to him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=21}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=92}}
* ''April 26.'' Bohemond's army crosses the [[Bosporus]] into Asia Minor.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=21}}
* ''May 14.'' The crusaders lay [[Siege of Nicaea|siege to Nicaea]] (now [[Iznik]] in Turkey) only after Bohemond's army reaches the town.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=119}}
* ''June 19.'' The Seljuk garrison of Nicaea surrenders to Alexios I's representatives. They do not allow the crusaders to enter the town, but distribute money among them.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=130}}
* ''July 1.'' [[Battle of Dorylaeum (1097)|Battle of Dorylaeum]]: the crusaders route the army of the [[Sultanate of Rum|Seljuk sultan of Rum]], [[Kilij Arslan I]].{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=4}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=134-137}}
* ''September 14.'' Tancred and [[Baldwin I of Jerusalem|Baldwin of Boulogne]] leave the main crusader army to launch a military campaign in Cilicia.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=142}}
* ''September 21.'' Tancred defeats the Seljuk garrison of [[Tarsus, Mersin|Tarsus]] and starts negotiations about their surrender.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=22}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=143}}
* ''September 22.'' Baldwin reaches Tarsus and talks the Seljuks into allowing his troops to enter the town. Outnumbered by Baldwin's troops, Tancred leaves Tarsus without resistance.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=143-144}}
* ''Late September.'' The Armenian ruler of Adana, Oshin, provides Tancred with 200 Armenian troops. As soon as Tancred reaches [[Mamistra]], the Seljuk garrison fleds the town and the local Armenians acknowledge Tancred as their ruler. Baldwin arrives at Mamistra and the two crusader armies clash near the town. Tancred puts a garrison in Mamistra before leaving Cilicia through the [[Belen Pass]] and joins the main crusader army.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=146-147}}
* ''{{circa}} October 15.'' The crusader leaders decide to lay siege Antioch without waiting for further reinforcements. Taking advantage of the crusaders' presence, the local Armenians expel the Seljuk garrison from [[Artah]]. Raymond IV occupies fortresses in the plains along the [[Orontes River]]. An English fleet in Byzantine service seizes [[Latakia]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=157-158}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=30, 32-33}}
* ''October 16.'' The governor of Antioch, [[Yağısıyan]] expels the Christians from the town. He sends envoys to the Seljuk rulers of [[Aleppo]], [[Damascus]] and [[Mosul]], seeking their assistance.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=21}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=19}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=156}}
* ''October 21.'' The crusaders lay [[Siege of Antioch|siege to Antioch]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=22}}
* ''November.'' A Genoese fleet arrives at [[St Symeon]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=188}}
* ''December 31.'' [[Duqaq]], the Seljuk ruler of Damascus leads relieving forces to Antioch, but Bohemond and [[Robert II, Count of Flanders]] force him to retreat.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=23-24}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=171-172}}
'''1098'''
* ''{{circa}} January 31.'' The Byzantine general, [[Tatikios]], leaves the crusader camp at Antioch. The crusaders regard his departure as a betrayal.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=179}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=34}}
* ''February 9.'' [[Battle of the Lake of Antioch]]: Bohemond, Robert II and [[Stephen, Count of Blois]] defeat the relieving army of [[Fakhr al-Mulk Radwan|Ridwan]], the Seljuk ruler of Aleppo. The crusaders capture [[Harem, Syria|Harim]].{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=25-26}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=184-185}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=29}}
* ''March 4.'' English ships arrive at [[St Symeon]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=188}}
* ''March 7.'' Yağısıyan's troops attack the crusaders across the Iron Gate on the Orontes River, but the crusaders annihilate them.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=192-193}}
* ''April–May.'' Secret negotiations between Bohemond and a wealthy burgher of Antioch, [[Firouz]], who is willing to give the crusaders access to the town.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=200-201}}
* ''May 4–25.'' [[Kerbogha]], the [[atabeg]] (or regent) of Mosul, besieges Baldwin of Boulogne at [[Edessa]] during his march towards Antioch.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=23}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=29-31}}
* ''May 29.'' The crusader leaders accept Bohemond's claim to rule Antioch if he achieves the surrender of the town.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=205}}
* ''June 3.'' Bohemond's troops enter Antioch with Firouz's assistance and the crusaders occupy the town. Yağısıyan's son, Shams ad-Daulah, resists them in the citadel.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=207-210}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=32-33}}
* ''June 4.'' Kerbogha's army reaches Antioch and lays siege to the town.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=23}}
* ''June 10.'' Crusaders start fleeing from Antioch because of starvation and fear.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=217}}
* ''June 14.'' A [[Provence|Provençal]] visionary, [[Peter Bartholomew]], claims to have miraculously found the [[Holy Lance]] in the [[Church of Saint Peter]]. The discovery of the alleged relic raises the crusaders' morale.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=221-225}}
* ''{{circa}} June 15.'' Alexios I abandons his campaign towards Antioch after Stephen of Blois, who deserted the crusaders' camp, informs him about the crusaders' desperate situation.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=93}}
* ''June 25.'' The crusaders elect Bohemond as commander-in-chief.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=232}}
* ''June 28.'' The crusaders break out of Antioch and route Kerbogha's troops, forcing him to abandon the siege. Shams ad-Daulah surrenders the citadel to the crusaders.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=234-239}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=34-35}}
