== Crusader state ==

=== Establishment ===
'''1098'''
* ''Early July.'' The crusader leaders send [[Hugh, Count of Vermandois]] and [[Baldwin II, Count of Hainaut]] to Constantinople to inform Alexios I about the conquest of Antioch. Bohemond takes control of most parts of the town, because most crusader leaders cede the districts that they has protected during the siege to him. Raymond IV retains his district and Peter Bartholomew declares him the protector of the Holy Lance.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=245, 255}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=37}}
* ''July 14.'' Bohemond grants the Church of Saint John, 30 nearby houses and a warehouse to the Genoese in Antioch.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=81}}
* ''{{circa}} July 17.'' An [[Duchy of Aquitaine|Aquitanian]] knight, [[Raymond Pilet d'Alès|Raymond Pilet]], assemble an army and invades the plateau near Antioch. He forces the Muslim peasants to convert to Christianity.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|p=248}}
* ''{{circa}} August 1.'' A plague decimates the crusaders. Their leaders retreat to the nearby regions to avoid infection.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=249-250}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=41}}
* ''August.'' Bohemond stays in Cilicia.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=29}}
* ''September 11.'' The crusader leaders urge the Pope in a letter to take over supreme command of their military expedition. In a separate document, Bohemond asks the Pope to annul the crusader leaders' treaties with Alexios I.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=40}}
* ''{{circa}} September 25.'' Raymond IV takes Albara. The crusaders massacre or enslave hundreds of Muslims. Raymond IV establishes the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Apamea#Diocese of Albara|Roman Catholic Diocese of Albara]] and appoints Peter of Narbonne as its first bishop. The [[Greek Orthodox Church of Antioch|Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch]], [[John the Oxite]], consecrates Peter.{{sfn|Asbridge|2004|pp=249-250}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=10}}
* ''November 18.'' The crusader leaders acknowledge Bohemond's right to rule Antioch, but he is required to promise to accompany them towards Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=23}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=41}}
* ''December 12.'' Raymond IV, Robert II and Bohemond [[Siege of Ma'arra|capture Maarrat al-Nu'man]]. The crusaders massacre the vast majority of the local Muslims.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=39-41}} 
'''1099'''
* ''Early January.'' Raymond IV denies to cede Maarrat al-Nu'man to Bohemond who returns to Antioch. Bohemond expels Raymond IV's troops from Antioch.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=37, 129}}{{sfn|Harris|2003|p=75}}
* ''March.'' Alexios I's envoys demand Antioch from Bohemond, but he refutes.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|pp=42-43}}
* ''Summer.'' After Byzantine troops are garrisoned at Latakia, Bohemond besieges the town.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=43}}
* ''Early September.'' 120 ships arrive at Latakia under the command of [[Dagobert of Pisa|Daimbert]], [[Archbishop of Pisa]]. The Pisans assist Bohemond against the Byzantines.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=25}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=62}}
* ''September.'' After returning from Jerusalem, Raymond IV, Robert II and other crusader leaders persuade the Pisans to abandon the siege of Latakia, forcing Bohemond to also lift the siege. Raymond IV tooks possession of Latakia on behalf of Alexios I.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=43}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=63}}
* ''December.'' Bohemond and Baldwin of Boulogne, who became the first crusader [[Count of Edessa]], come to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=25}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=45}}
* ''December 25.'' Daimbert is installed as the [[Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem]]. Bohemond swears fealty to him for his lands. Daimbert appoints Latin priests to the sees of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Edessa|Edessa]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tarsus|Tarsus]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Mamistra|Mamistra]] and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Artah|Artah]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=25}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=15}}
'''1100'''
* ''Spring.'' A Byzantine fleet expels the crusader (or Frank) garrisons from the towns on the Cilician coast.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=64}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=16}}
* ''June.'' Bohemond defeats Ridwan at Kella.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=51}}
* ''{{circa}} August 15.'' The Armenian prince, [[Gabriel of Melitene]], seeks Bohemond's assistance against the [[Danishmends|Danishmend]] emir [[Gazi Gümüshtigin]]. Bohemond hurries to Melitene (now [[Malatya]] in Turkey), but Gazi Gümüshtigin captures him. Baldwin of Boulogne relieves Melitene and garrisons his troops in the town.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=51}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=74}}  
* ''Summer.'' Raymond IV leaves Latakia for Constantinople to meet with Alexios I. After being accused of cooperating with the Byzantines, Patriarch John the Oxite leaves Antioch first for a nearby Orthodox monastery, then for Constantinople. Bohemond appoints [[Bernard of Valence]] as the first [[Latin Patriarch of Antioch]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=45}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=17}}{{sfn|Harris|2003|p=81}}
'''1101'''
* ''Spring.'' Tancred assumes regency for the captive Bohemond. He invades Cilicia and forces the Byzantines to abandon Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=52}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=68}}
* ''Summer.'' Tancred lays siege to Latakia. He grants the Genoese a share in the revenues collected at the harbours of St Symeon and Latakia.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=52}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=81}}
'''1102'''
* After his return to Syria, Raymond IV withdraws his troops from Latakia and marches to Tripoli to lay [[Siege of Tripoli|siege to the town]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=70}}
'''1102-1103'''
* The emir of Homs, [[Janah ad-Daula]], captures the fortress of Asfouna and massacres its Frank garrison.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=53}}
'''1103'''
* ''April-May.'' Tancred occupies Latakia.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=81}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=27}}
* ''May.'' Patriarch Bernard and the Armenian ruler of Raban and [[Fortress of Kaysun|Kaisun]], [[Kogh Vasil]], ransom of Bohemond who returns to Antioch.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=53}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=27}}
* ''Summer.'' Bohemond makes plundering raids in Aleppan territory and forces Ridwan to pay a tribute.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=55}}
* ''Autumn.'' The Byzantines capture the Cilician coast.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=27}}
'''1104'''
* ''Spring.'' [[Jikirmish]], the atabeg of Mosul, and the Artuqid emir, [[Sökmen (Artuqid)|Sökmen]], invade the [[County of Edessa]]. Bohemond leads a relieving army to Edessa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=27}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=55}}
* ''May 7.'' [[Battle of Harran]]: Jikirmish and Sökmen route the united Antiochene and Edessan armies. [[Baldwin II of Jerusalem|Baldwin II, Count of Edessa]], and his vassal, [[Joscelin I of Courtenay]], [[Lord of Turbessel]], are captured. Tancred assumes the government of Edessa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=28}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=55}}
* ''Late May.'' Ridwan takes Maarrat al-Nu'man, Artah, Kafartab and other Antiochene border forts. A Byzantine fleet captures Latakia, but the Norman garrison resists them in the citadel.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=28}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=72}}
* ''Autumn.'' Bohemond leaves Antioch for Europe to call for a new crusade. Tancred again assumes the regency for him in Antioch. Bohemond's cousin, [[Richard of Salerno]], is made the governor of Edessa.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=28}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=73}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|pp=16-17, 83}}
'''1105'''
* ''February 28.'' Raymond IV dies and his cousin, [[William II Jordan|William Jordan]] continues the [[siege of Tripoli]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=28}}
* ''{{circa}} April 20.'' [[Battle of Artah]]: Tancred routes Ridwan.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=84}}
* ''April-May.'' Tancred occupies most fortresses near Aleppo.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=57}}
'''1106'''
* ''Spring.'' Tancred unsuccessfully besieges [[Apamea, Syria|Apamea]].{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=60}}
* ''May 26.'' [[Pope Paschal II]]'s [[papal legate|legate]] preaches a new crusade and names Bohemond as its leader at a council in Poitiers. Bohemond marries [[Philip I of France]]'s daughter, [[Constance of France, Princess of Antioch|Constance]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|pp=29, 145}}
* ''September.'' Bohemond's letter to the Pope is the first extant document in which he styles himself as "prince of Antioch".{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=131}}
* ''August.'' Tancred captures Apamea with the support of its former Muslim ruler's sons and grants them estates in the principality.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=60}}
'''1107'''
* ''October.'' Bohemond invades the Byzantine Empire from Epirus and lays siege to Dyrrachium. Venetian and Byzantine fleets deny supplies to his troops. Alexios I withdraws his troops from Cilicia, charging Oshin with its defence.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=29}}{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=626}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=62}}
* ''November-October.'' Tancred and a Genoese fleet capture Mamistra.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=29}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=62-63}} 
'''1107/1108'''
* Tancred captures Latakia from the Byzantines.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=64}}
'''1108'''
* ''{{circa}} August 15.'' Baldwin II is released from captivity in Mosul. Tancred denies to return Edessa to him unless Baldwin II swears allegiance to him. The Armenisans support the Byzantines in recapturing Mamistra.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=359}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=63}}
* ''September.'' [[Treaty of Devol]]: Bohemond accepts Byzantine sovereignty and agrees to restore John the Oxite in Antioch; he also promises to persuade Tancred to cede Latakia and Cilicia to the Byzantines. Bohemond returns to southern Italy and does not make efforts to enforce Tancred to implementat the treaty.{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|p=626}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|pp=75-76, 80-81}}
* ''September 18.'' Patriarch Bernard mediates a reconciliation between Tancred and Baldwin II to prevent an armed conflict. Tancred restores Edessa to Baldwin II.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=30}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=112-113}}
* ''Late September.'' Tancred routes the united armies of [[Jawali Saqawa]], Baldwin II, Joscelin I and Kogh Vasil near Turbessel.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=30}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=113}}
* Tancred styles himself as "prince of Antioch" in two charters.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=130}}
'''Late 1108/Early 1109'''
* Raymond IV's son, [[Bertrand, Count of Toulouse|Bertrand]], lands at St Symeon and demands his father's districts in Antioch. He urges Tancred to jointly capture [[Jabala]], but Tancred banishes him from the principality.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=64, 115}}
'''1109.'''
* ''March.'' Bertrand demands Raymond IV's inheritance near Tripoli, including fortresses captured by William Jordan. William Jordan swears fealty to Tancred in return for his assistance against Bertrand.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=30}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=115}}
* ''April.'' Baldwin I summons Tancred and William Jordan in the name of the "church of Jerusalem" to the crusaders' camp at Tripoli, accusing them of injustices against Bertrand, Baldwin II and Joscelin I. The crusader leaders' council obliges Tancred to restore lands to Baldwin II and Joscelin. Baldwin I grants Tancred the [[Principality of Galilee|Galilee]] in the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]]. William Jordan is allowed to retain Tortosa (now [[Tartus]] in Syria) and Arqah as Tancred's vassal, but he is soon murdered and his domain is seized by Bertrand.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=30}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=117-119}}
* ''May.'' Tancred captures Baniyas and Jabala.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=64}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=98}}
'''1110'''
* ''April-May.'' [[Mawdud]], the atabeg of Mosul, [[Sökmen el-Kutbî]], the [[Shah-Armens|Seljuq ruler of Armenia]], and the Artuqid emir [[Ilghazi]], invade Edessa. Baldwin II accuses Tancrod of having incited the invasion.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=99}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=120}}
* ''June.'' Baldwin I mediates a reconciliation between Tancred and Baldwin II, persuading Tancred to abandon his claims to sovereignty over Edessa.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=120}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=31}}
'''1111'''
* ''March 5/7.'' Bohemond dies in Bari. His son, [[Bohemond II of Antioch|Bohemond II]], inherits Taranto and Tancred continues to rule Antioch.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=31}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=136}}{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=304}}
* ''Spring.'' Tancred fortifies Tell ibn-Mas'shar near [[Shaizar]]. The [[Munqidhites|Munqidhite]] emir of Shaizar pays a tribute of 10,000 dinars to Tancred.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=61}}
* ''September.'' The emir of Shaizar makes an alliance with Mawdud. Mawdud invades the principality, but he avoids a pitched battle after reinforcements come from Jerusalem and Tripoli to Tancred's rescue.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=61}}
* ''Autumn.'' The Byzantine envoy, [[Manuel Boutoumites]], persuades Bertrand in Tripoli to promise military assistance to Alexios I against Tancred.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|pp=85-86}}
* ''October.'' Alexios I grants commercial privileges to the Pisans who pledge to fight against the Byzantines' enemies.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=31}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|pp=87-90}}
'''1112'''
* ''February.'' Bertrand dies. His son and successor, [[Pons, Count of Tripoli|Pons]], takes possession of the estates that Bertrand held in fief from Tancred with Tancred's consession.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=103}}
* ''Easter.'' After lengthy negotiations, Baldwin I and Joscelin I refutes to conclude an alliance with the Byzantines against Antioch.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=86}}
* ''Summer-Autumn.'' Kogh Vasil captures Hisn Mansur. Tancred invades Kogh Vasil's domains and captures Raban. He restores Raban to Kogh Vasil in return for two fortresses.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=67}}
* ''December 12.'' Tancred dies.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=31}} 
'''1113'''
* ''Early.'' Tancred's nephew, [[Roger of Salerno|Roger]], becomes the ruler of Antioch and marries Baldwin II's sister, [[Cecilia of Le Bourcq]]. Tancred is styled as prince in contemporaneous documents. He demands tribute from the Muslim rulers of Aleppo and Shaizar.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=69, 139-140, 167}}
'''1114'''
* ''November 13.'' An earthquake destroys the citadel at Mamistra and its garrison.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=69}}
* ''November 29.'' An earthquake demolishes parts of Antioch and Marash (now [[Kahramanmaraş]] in Turkey).{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=69}}
'''1115'''
* Pons marries Tancred's widow, [[Cecile of France]]. He takes possession of her dowry{{mdash}}Rugia and Arzhgan{{mdash}}in the Principality of Antioch, 
* ''February.'' The Seljuq Sultan [[Muhammad I Tapar]] sents his general, [[Bursuq ibn Bursuq]], to Syria to restore his rule.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=104}}
* ''Early Summer.'' Tancred concludes an alliance with Ilghazi and [[Toghtekin]], the atabeg of Damascus, against Bursuq ibn Bursuq.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=69}}
* ''September 14.'' [[Battle of Sarmin]]: Tancred annihilates Bursuq's army in the valley of Danith.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=104}}
'''1116'''
* Tancred and Pons besiege [[Marqab]], but they cannot capture it.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=73}}
'''{{circa}} 1117'''
* Antiochene troops seize [[Citadel of Salah Ed-Din|Saone]], Balatanos and Marqab.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=73}}
'''1117'''
* Yaruqtash, the actual ruler of Aleppo, cedes the fortress at al-Qubba to Roger, enabling him to extract duty on the pilgrims making the [[Hajj]] from Aleppo.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=73}}
'''1118'''
* ''Summer.'' Ilghazi cannot prevent Roger and the Armenian Leo from capturing [[Azaz]] near Aleppo.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=74}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=122}}
'''1119'''
* ''Spring.'' Antiochene troops take [[Bizaah]]. The burghers of Aleppo seeks Ilghazi's assistance.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=74}}
* ''June 28.'' [[Battle of Ager Sanguinis|Battle of the "Field of Blood"]]: Ilghazi almost annihilates the Antiochene army; Roger perishes in the battlefield.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=123}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=93}}

=== Under regents' rule === 
'''1119'''
* ''Early August.'' Baldwin II, who became king of Jerusalem in 1118, and Pons hurry to Antioch to defend the principality against Ilghazi. The Antiochene barons elect Baldwin II as regent for the absent Bohemond II. Ilghazi captures al-Atharib and Zardana, the Munqidhites seize Maarrat al-Nu'man and the nearby fortresses.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|pp=75, 80, 143-144}}
* ''August 14.'' [[Battle of Hab]]: Baldwin II forces Ilghazi and Toghtekin to withdraw from the principality.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=132}}
'''1120'''
* ''May-June.'' Ilghazi and Toghtekin invade the principality, but Baldwin II prevents them from conquering new territories. Ilghazi agrees to sign a one-year truce.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=81}}
'''1121'''
* ''April-June.'' Baldwin II makes raids in the region of al-Atharib, forcing Ilghazi to renew the truce.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=82}}
* ''July-September.'' Taking advantage of a conflict between Ilghazi and his son, Sulaiman, Antiochene troops seize Zardana and Baldwin pillages a number of villages near Aleppo.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=82}}
'''1122'''
* ''July.'' Ilghazi lays siege to Zardana, but Baldwin II relieves the town.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=83}}
* ''November-December.'' After Ilghazi's death, Baldwin II occupies [[al-Bab]] and Albara.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=83}}
'''1123'''
* ''April 9.'' [[Badr ad-Daulah Suleiman]], the atabeg of Aleppo, makes peace with Baldwin II and cedes al-Atharib to him.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=84}}
* ''April 18.'' [[Belek Ghazi|Nur al-Daulak Balak]], ambushes Baldwin II and imprisons him in Kharput (now [[Elazığ]] in Turkey).{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=138}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=36}}
* ''April-May.'' Balak captures Albara.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=84}}
'''1124'''
* ''January.'' Balak, Toghtekin and [[Aqsunqur al-Bursuqi]], the atabeg of Mosul, besiege Azaz, but a crusader army force them to abandon the siege.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=84}}
* ''Spring.'' Balak's troops raid the region of Azaz.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=84}}
* ''May 6.'' Salak dies fighting against a rebellious vassal.{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=97-98}}
* ''August 29.'' Ilghazi's son, Timurtash, releases Baldwin II in return for 80,000 dinars and a promise to surrender the fortresses of al-Atharib, Zardana, Azaz and Kafartab to him.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=84}}
* ''September 6.'' Patriarch Bernard forbids Baldwin II to cede Antiochene territories to Timurtash.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=85}}
* ''October 29.'' Baldwin II lays [[Siege of Aleppo (1124)|siege to Aleppo]]. Timurtash fails to support the citizens who seek Aqsunqur's assistance.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=37}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=87}}
'''1125'''
* ''January 29.'' Aqsunqur forces Baldwin II to lift the siege of Aleppo.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=87}}
* ''June 11.'' [[Battle of Azaz (1125)|Battle of Azaz]]: Baldwin II defeats Aqsunqur.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=143}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=87}}
'''1126'''
* ''October 23-November 22.'' Bohemond II arrives at Antioch. He is installed as prince in Baldwin II's presence. Bohemond II marries Baldwin II's daughter, [[Alice of Antioch|Alice]].{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=39}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=147}}
'''1127'''
* ''Early.'' Bohemond II captures Kafartab.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=89}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=152}}
* ''April.'' The Seljuk Sultan [[Mahmud II of Great Seljuq|Mahmud II]] appoints [[Imad ad-Din Zengi]] to administer Mosul and Aleppo.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=39}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|p=113}}
* ''Summer.'' Bohemond II visits Cilicia. Joscelin I invades Antioch with Seljuk reinforcements. Baldwin II and Patriarch Bernard mediate a reconciliation between the two crusader ruler.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=39}}
* ''December.'' Bohemond II launches a raid against Aleppo.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=90}}
'''1128'''
* ''May-June.'' [[Roger II of Sicily]] occupies Bohemond II's southern Italian domains.{{sfn|Norwich|1992|p=312}}
'''1129'''
* [[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I]], the Armenian ruler of Cilicia, captures Anazarba.{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=90}}{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=22}}
'''1130'''
* ''February.'' Bohemond II invades Cilicia, but Thoros I's ally, Gazi Gümüshtikin routes him on the river Jihan. Bohemond II dies fighting in the battlefield. Baldwin II hurries to Antioch, but Alice tries to prevent him from assuming control of the principality, but he gains entrance to the town with Antiochene nobles' assistance. He appoints Joscelin I to administer the principality on behalf of Bohemond II and Alice's daughter, [[Constance of Antioch|Constance]], and exiles Alice to Latakia. Roger II claims Antioch as Bohemond II's last surviving male relative, but he does not take steps to assert his claim.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=40}}{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=221}}{{sfn|Maalouf|1984|pp=115-116}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=101}}
* ''Spring.'' Zengi's military commander, Sawar, attacks al-Atharib and other Antiochene fortresses.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=24}}
'''{{circa}} 1131'''
* [[Leo I, Prince of Armenia]], the Armenian ruler of Cilicia, captures most towns on the Cilician plain, enabling the nomadic Turkomans to freely invade the principality from Anatolia.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=22}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=106}}
'''1130s'''
* Antiochene nobles offer Constance's hand to [[Manuel I Komnenos|Manuel]], a younger son of the Byzantine Emperor [[John II Komnenos]]{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=22}}
'''1131'''
* ''August 21.'' Baldwin II dies. His daughter, [[Melisende of Jerusalem|Melisende]], and her husband, [[Fulk, King of Jerusalem|Fulk of Anjou]], succeeds him in Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=149}}
* ''September.'' Joscelin I dies. His son, [[Joscelin II of Edessa|Joscelin II]], inherits Edessa. Alice assumes authority in the principality with the assistance of the brothers [[William of Zardana]] and [[Garenton of Saone]]. Other nobles urge Fulk to intervene.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=152}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=160}}
'''1132'''
* ''Early.'' Fulk defeats Alice's allies at Chastel Rouge. He appoints [[Rainald I Masoir]] as regent for Constance. Taking advantage of the civil war, Turkomans attack Kafartab and Maarrat al-Nu'man.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=25}}{{sfn|Asbridge|2000|p=161}}
'''1133'''
* ''Spring-Summer.'' Sawar makes pillaging raids against Antioch and Edessa, but Fulk defeats him at [[Qinnasrin]]. Fulk and the Antiochene nobles decide to offer Constance's hand to [[Raymond of Poitiers]] (the younger son of [[William IX, Duke of Aquitaine]]). Sawar's raids continue after Fulk's return to Jerusalem.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}
'''1135'''
* ''Early summer.'' Patriarch Bernard dies. The clergymen assemble to elect his successor, but the burghers proclaim [[Ralph of Domfront]] as patriarch. He fails to ask the Pope to confirm his election and emphasizes that the see of Antioch was established by [[Saint Peter the Apostle]].{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=30, 32}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=42}}
'''1136'''
* ''April.'' Raymond of Poitiers arrives at Antioch. He swears fealty to Patriarch Ralph before the Patriarch authorizes him to marry the 8-year-old Constance. Raymond assumes the government of the principality.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=41}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=103}}{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=22}}
* ''Summer.'' Raymond invades Cilicia and captures Leo I who swears fealty to him. Raymond seizes the towns in western Cilicia.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|pp=106-107}}{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=27}}
'''1137'''
* ''July.'' Zengi besieges Fulk in the castle of Montferrand (at present-day Baarin in Syria). Raymond leaves a relieving army to Montferrand, but Fulk surrenders it to Zengi before Raymond's arrival.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=43}}
* ''July-August.'' John II occupies Cilicia. Danishmend troops besiege Marash and Kaisun, but they abandon the siege because of the advance of the Byzantine army.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|pp=117-118}}{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=29}}
* ''August 29.'' John II lays siege to Antioch.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=43}}
* ''September.'' Raymond swears fealty to John II and promises to renounce Antioch in return for Aleppo, Shaizar, Homs and Emesa after these towns are conquered.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=121}}
'''1138'''
* ''Early.'' Raymond orders the arrest of the Muslim merchants in Antioch.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=126}}
* ''Spring.'' The united Byzantine and crusader armies unsuccessfully besiege Aleppo, but they take al-Atarib and Kafartab. They lays siege to Shaizar, but John II abandons the siege in exchange for a tribute. With Raymond's support, two clerics accuse Patriarch Ralph of [[simony]] to achieve his deposition, but Ralph travels to Rome.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=129}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=34-35}}
* ''May.'' John II enters Antioch and demands it from Raymond. After experiencing the burghers' protest, John II withdraws his troops from the town. [[Pope Innocent II]] confirms Ralph's election as patriarch and restores his jurisdiction over the archbishopric of Tyre.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=43}}{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=35}}
'''Late 1138-early 1139'''
* Zengi captures Bizaah, Maarrat al-Nu'man and al-Atharib.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=33}}
'''1139'''
* ''Spring.'' A Sicilian fleet accompanies Patriarch Ralph back to Antioch. Raymond forbids him to enter the town and the Patriarch settles in the County of Edessa.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|p=35}}
* Earthquake destroys al-Atharib and Zardana.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=33}}
* Sawar invades the principality, but Raymond overcomes him.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=34}}
'''1140'''
* ''December 2.'' A synod convoked by the papal legate, [[Alberic of Ostia]], deposes Patriarch Ralph and elects [[Aimery of Limoges]] as patriarch.{{sfn|Hamilton|2016|pp=36, 38}}
'''1140/1141'''
* Turkomans launch a pillaging raid against the principality.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=34}}
'''1141'''
* Antiochene troops pillage Kafartab and [[Sarmin]]. Sawar and Turkomans raid the principality as far as the gates of Antioch.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=34}}{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=45}}
'''1142'''
* Invading forces from Aleppo rout Antiochene troops near Harim and at the Iron Bridge.{{sfn|Buck|2017|pp=34-35}}
* ''September-October.'' John II leads his forces to northern Syria and demands Antioch from Raymond. Byzantine troops pillage the suburbs of Antioch before they withdraw to winter in Cilicia.{{sfn|Lock|2006|p=45}}{{sfn|Lilie|1993|pp=136-137}}
'''1143'''
* ''April 8.'' John I dies in hunting accident in Cilicia.{{sfn|Lilie|1993|p=137}}{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=132}}
* ''April/May.'' Raymond unsuccessfully besieges Bizaah.{{sfn|Buck|2017|p=35}}
'''1144'''
* ''December 23.'' Zengi captures Edessa.{{sfn|Barber|2012|p=180}}

